There is an issue with the example mentioned in the following section

> 13.5 Don’t chain variable assignments.

**Accessing the value of `a` would throw an Uncaught ReferenceError: a is not defined.**

[https://github.com/airbnb/javascript#variables--no-chain-assignment](url)

````
// bad
(function example() {
  // JavaScript interprets this as
  // let a = ( b = ( c = 1 ) );
  // The let keyword only applies to variable a; variables b and c become
  // global variables.
  let a = b = c = 1;
}());

console.log(a); // undefined
console.log(b); // 1
console.log(c); // 1

``` `

From eslint v3.9.0 this option is deprecated.

I see that in the base this option is off and with a TODO comment

```
// suggest using Reflect methods where applicable
// http://eslint.org/docs/rules/prefer-reflect
// TODO: enable?
'prefer-reflect': 'off',
```
Since current eslint dependency version is 3.19.0, I would suggest at least to replace the _**enable?**_ comment with a **_deprecated rule and to be removed in a later version_**?
